description:
1/4/2020: 

We went to Turtle Pond at Pepperwood Preserve. Unfortunately, we saw 6 dead newts and 3 (2 adults and 1 baby) alive newts. They were on the rims of the pond. They were found all over Turtle Pond not in just one specific area of Turtle Pond. We have some theories as to why they look mangled and have their guts left but weâ€™re not sure.
place_guess: Pepperwood Preserve Rd, Santa Rosa, CA, US

Along the side of its body were a single row of red dots, stretching from its neck to its tail. Its body was a dimming black, its scales rather shiny. Its head was roughly 3/4   of an inch in length, and 1/3 of an inch wide. It had bright red patches toward the back of its head, behind its eyes along with another red patch below both eyes. The frond and rachis length varied in each fern.

This snake was found at the edge of a small pond. He/She was very calm and allowed many people to hold him/her. The tongue of this snake was red with a black tip. The length of the vent to the tail is ~6 inches and the entire length of the snake is ~17 inches.The black scales of the snake have a slight reflective blue hue to them when in sunlight.

description:
This plant was growing in large groups near a small body of water. The plants were in broad sunlight and had no natural shade. The stems range from 6-10 inches tall with a dark purple color towards the top and a greener color towards the bottom. The blossoms are a fluffy white and light lavender color. The leaves are green that branch off the stem. The entire plant is covered in a thin fuzz on the leaves and stem. 

Source(s):

-The Laws Field Guide to the Sierra Nevada by John Muir Laws

description:
This small scorpion was found under a rock in partial shade. There was some moisture under the rock as well as some dry dirt. 3 other similar scorpions were found under rocks within a 10 meter radius. The scorpion is roughly 4 cm long with its tail curled in. The head and tail are a darker color compared to the thick abdomen. This was the largest scorpion found amongst the other 3.

Source(s):

-The Laws Field Guide to the Sierra Nevada by John Muir Laws

description: These ferns were growing around a small creek. Underneath there was a lot of dead fern leaves and a light layer of water. The new leaves were a mix of deep and light green. The new leaves did not have anything on their undersides. Each stem appears to grow out of the base of the fern and the pinna (leaves) grow symmetrically on either side of the stem. The older leaves are starting to turn brown and have sori on their undersides that are light brown dashes about and eight of an inch long. They also grow symmetrically from either side of the pinna (leaf). There are many flies in the area and movement in the ferns implies that there are larger animals under/in the fern. The ferns were all around 6'x6'x6'.

description:
This Jerusalem Cricket or "Potato Bug" was found underneath a 10 inch rock. The rock was covered in moss and was moist underneath as well as the soil below. The bug was found burrowed in the soil underneath the rock. The body and thorax is 3cm in length and 5.5cm with the antennae. Abdomen has dark stripes divided by skinny tan ones. The hind legs or thighs are significantly thicker than the other legs, thus indicating that this creature jumps. Each leg has a small hook at the end. Each leg has small spikes on them too.

description:
This fire red dragonfly was spotted near a pond top a blade of grass. This was the only red dragonfly I spotted among many other Common Spreadwing dragonflies. The length of this particular dragonfly was roughly 40mm, but I was not able to get a precise measurement. The wings jet out perpendicular of the body. Each wing has one red speck towards the upper/outer edge. The head, thorax, abdomen, and eyes all are red. This dragonfly looks similar to a Flame Skimmer dragonfly but it is shorter in length, has a different wing pattern, and is brighter red in color.

Source(s):

-Common Dragonflies of California by Kathy Biggs

Camera: Canon EOS 60D

description:
This light blue and black dragon fly was spotted near a pond and hanging on a blade of grass. This species of dragonfly has wings that spread out, thus making it part of the spreadwing family. The wings do not jet out perpendicular to the body though. This particular dragonfly has light blue eyes, as well as blue on the thorax and on the abdominal segments. This slender dragonfly is roughly 40mm long. I was not able to get a precise measurement of the dragonfly though.

Source(s):

-Common Dragonflies of California by Kathy Biggs

description:
These two Milkweed Beetles appear to be mating on spreading dogbane (apocynum androsaemifolium). They are each 0.5in long. Their distinct metallic blue color is a key indicator of the species. Many other mating Milkweed Beetles were in the vicinity as well. These beetles were found next to a pond and were found in direct sunlight. The Dogbane plant appeared to be a source of food for the beetles due to it being partially eaten on the leaves.

Source(s): 

-The Laws Field Guide to the Sierra Nevada by John Muir Laws

-Kaufman Field Guide to Insects of North America by Eric R. Eaton and Kenn Kaufman

-The Peterson Field Guide Series: A Field Guide to Pacific States Wildfolwers

description: This beetle was between the size of a quarter and a half dollar. I found it swimming near my legs in a pond. It has two very long back legs that it seems to use to swim. It was a fairly fast swimmer as well. Along the sides of those legs are hair-like things that look almost like fins, but are separated into little pieces. As I said before, the pieces do look like hair and they would flow similar to human hair in the water. The top was very smooth and a deep brown. It had one long strip down its body and along the very edges of the shell was some small black dots. The underside was more of an amber color and had more legs, I believe there were four more. It also had two antennae.

description: This plant covers most of Double Pond in Pepperwood. The center of the pond is the only part not covered by the plant. It has red stems with soft and thin tan roots that come off the stem like hair. The plant overlaps so it creates a layer over the water. It has small frogs, dragonflies, and spiders crawling on it. There appear to be two different leaves, one like needles coming off the red stem similar to pine needles, but much softer. The other ones stood up above the water and were around six inches long and at most an inch wide. They layered up  in a way that made it look like the plant might flower. The look leaves almost looked like paddles. This plant reminds me of lily pads, like the way their roots grow.

description:
Small fungus growing on top the stump of a douglas-fir tree. The stump was weathered (due to the grey color) and has been there for a while. It is roughly 4.5 cm long. The color is mostly light brown with lighter & darker brown patches. The texture is hard, either because of the type of fungi or possibly because of time, climate, and/or sun exposure. The fungi feels dry and is porous when examined up close. It was found on top a stump that had moss growing on it, indicating that there was moisture in the vicinity. The fungus was in a shaded region with partial sunlight among other and douglas fir trees.

Photos taken with: Nikon Coolpix S33

description: This insect was found under a rock in the grassland approximately 2 meters from a small pool of water (only a few inches in length). The rock was stuck deep into the ground. When the rock was lifted the hole it created was over 7 inches in depth. When the rock was lifted up the insect tried to keep digging into the earth. The black insect was about 1.5 inches in length. The beetle is shiny. The abdomen of the insect is larger than its head and thorax. The beetle has two antennae and two attachments on its lower jaw. The legs of the beetle are thickest on the top part of the leg and get thinner towards the end of the leg. The last part of the leg has bumps and grips that aid the beetle when it crawls. The end of the abdomen is pointed. The beetle was very quick and did not like direct sunlight.

description: The dragonfly was found around the edge of turtle pond, over 8 meters away from the water. There were thick grasses around the edge of the pond and the dragonfly was perched on the dead stalk of one of the grasses. It has a bright red body with 4 wings. The dragonfly has big red eyes that take up the majority of the dragonfly's head. It is about 2-3 inches in length. The dragonfly periodically moves off the stalk, hoovers in the air and then lands on the stalk again, which indicates that the dragonfly may be territorial. The wings of the dragonfly are transparent and very shiny. The top wings of the dragonfly are about the same length of the dragonfly's body. The dragonfly's bottom wings are slightly smaller than the length of the dragonfly's body. There are many other different species of dragonflies around turtle pond.

description: The baby newt was found under a rock near turtle pond on a very hot/sunny day. The mud under the rock was very moist/wet. There is no canopy cover over the rock. The rock was about 3 meters from the water in turtle pond (the water in the pond had receded a great distance due to the drought). The newt was brown/grey in color. The newt is about 1.5 inches long. The newt did not like the direct sunlight. When the rock was lifted, the newt immediately moved towards the cool grass (that was located around the edges of the rock). There was another newt under the same rock and under other rocks around the dry pond.

description: This plant was found in forest duff under 50-60% canopy cover, mostly oak trees. There were about 1-2 plants per square foot so, presumably, they do not need much water as they were found in a dry area during a drought. The plant is approximately 44 cm tall with 3-4 mm diameter spike balls. The spike balls grow in clusters and when they come in contact with fabric, they tend to stick onto the fabric and are quite difficult to remove. The plant's leaves are curly and grow further down on the plant, not near to where the spike balls are. The plant is brown and appears to be very dry.

Two weeks ago there were 5-6 rough skin newts observed approximately 5 meters away in a pool. The newt was about 6 inches long. It had very rough/ bumpy skin. The skin was gray/light brown in color. The underside of the newt was bright orange. The newt may have golden/black eyes (it was hard to see them). When I observed the newt it was a hot day. The newt attempted to avoid the sun and moved deeper into the mud and shady areas as I was observing it. I did not observe any other newts in the area. There were many wasps around the water.

description: This flower is bright pink and has five petals. The petals have an oblong shape and are rounded at the tips. There are lines of a slightly darker pink running through the middle of the petals. The flower is 1 cm in length from petal tip to petal tip. It has a green center that is circular and slightly "bleeds out"  onto the petals. The stamens reach straight out of the center of the flower and the pollen on the anther is bright yellow. There are approximately 4-5 stamens per flower. The flower was found in a grassland growing near a Himalayan blackberry bush, poison oak, and other grasses.  The other grasses are taller than the flower. The entire plant stands about 32 cm tall. There were 10-12 of the same flower growing in the same 4 meter by 4 meter area. There was no canopy cover over the flowers. The stem and leaves of the plant are bright green. The flowers are located at the top of the plant. The leaves are also located at the top of the plant, near the base of the flowers. The buds that contain the new flowers are brown/yellow in color and are very long.

description: The fungi was found growing on a dead branch. When I observed the fungus, it was a very hot/sunny day and there was no canopy cover over the dead branch. The approximate average length of the fungi was 5-6 inches across. There were other shelf fungi on the bottom branch that are larger and a different color than the fungi I observed. The fungi is very ridged and strong. Some of the fungus is white with brown/amber stripes throughout. Other fungus on the branch have black, grey, white and amber/brown stripes. I noticed that the fungus that was growing under the log was a lighter color than the fungus that was growing on top or on the side of the log. Some of the fungus look like clam shells and other fungus have ridges on their outer edges. Some of the fungus grows in clusters, other fungus on the branch grows solitary.

Some of the fungus on the branch looks like half circles or clam shells. Other fungus on the branch have ridged edges. There was no canopy cover over the fungi and it was a very hot/sunny day. The fungi is very strong and rigid ( I was not able to pry the fungi off the branch). The outer edges of some of the fungi are black (the outer edges almost look burnt). description: The arachnid was found in a tunnel made of web that was stretched over an old log. The web also stretches over leaf debris and sticks. The web was a rough rectangle/oval shape that was about 10 inches by 5 inches. The web got increasingly thicker as it neared the tunnel. The arachnid's tunnel was towards the right side of the web. The web/arachnid was found on a hillside in an oak forest. I observed the arachnid sitting in its tunnel. When I approached the web too closely, the arachnid retreated deeper into the tunnel, but emerged 1-2 minutes later. The spider never crawled completely out of the tunnel. Within the same 6 meter by 6 meter area, there were about 7-8 other webs that looked exactly like the spider web I observed. The front of the arachnid was light brown and the back of the arachnid seemed a darker brown. The spider had a thin white striped pattern on its front 4 legs (I was not able to clearly observe the back 4 legs). The arachnid also had two attachments near its mouth (I could not determine if the attachments are fangs).

description: This insect was found in an oak woodland near a grassland. The organism was walking through the leaf litter and sparse grasses. There were over 5 in the same organism 2 foot by 2 foot area. Some similar organisms spotted in the same area had the same body structure as the one I observed, but were brown/ dark brown in color. I am not sure if the white organism I observed is the same species as the brown organisms (maybe a juvenile of that species) or if it is a different species altogether. The insect was very fast and extremely hard to catch. When I observed the organism the temperature was over 80 degrees Fahrenheit. It has two black eyes and long antennae (about as long as the length of the insect's body). It is about 1 cm long. The insect has six legs that are hairy on the upper part of the leg. It has jointed back legs. The insect is yellow/white/clear in color. The abdomen of the insect has unusual striations and is a darker color than the rest of the body. There are two tiny attachments off the back of the insect's abdomen. There are no clear distinctions between the head, thorax, and abdomen.

When I got within 3 meters of the rock it was sunning on, the lizard fluidly jumped to another rock and then scampered off. The lizard's camouflage blended in very well with the rocky terrain of the area. The lizard was found in a grassland area with a few trees nearby. It was about 3-4 inches in length.

description: The skink was found under a rock in an oak forest. There was about 80% canopy cover. Although the temperature was about 85 degrees Fahrenheit, when the skink was observed, it was very cool under the trees. There were numerous rocks in the same hilltop where we found the skink. The skink has a cobalt blue tail. The body of the skink is very slippery/silky but not wet or moist. It has 4 legs with 5 toes on each foot. It has claws on the ends of the toes. The skink's back is dark brown and has 4 whites stripes that are white/tan. The underside of the sink is white and light yellow/tan. The skin has a pointed snout that is rounded on the end. Its eyes are black. The skink was very hard to catch because it escaped many times. It was very quick in the dirt and leaf litter.

description: The rattlesnake was found under dead branches and a dead log on a hot/sunny day. I did not observe other rattlesnakes in the area, but I did see numerous western fence lizards in the same 6 meter by 6 meter area. The rattlesnake has a diamond shaped head and a rattle on the end of its tail. The body of the rattlesnake is faint green with black markings. The black markings along its spine are oval shapes. There are small diamond shapes along the sides of the rattlesnake that are alternating. The black designs become darker as they near the "tail" of the rattlesnake. On the tail of the rattlesnake there are black stripes. It is 1.5 -2 feet in length. When first observed the rattlesnake was slithering through dry grass. It then proceeded to coil and puff up as I got closer. When the rattlesnake "puffed" it sounded like the snake was sucking in air. The snake did not shake its rattle when I was observing it (I was at a safe distance away), but it continually flicked its tongue up and down. The top of the tongue was black and the bottom of the tongue was pink.

description: Found inside an old, hollowed out stump on a spider web during a hot/sunny day. The old stump is partially shaded by 2 trees. The stump is located on the outside of an oak woodland near a grassland. It has a very small body (approximately .5 centimeters long). It also has no distinguishable body regions (almost as if the whole body is fused together). It has 8 legs that are 3-4 centimeters long and has 2 joints. I am not sure if the web pictured is the organisms web or if it is caught in the web. The web is very sticky and strong (it did not break when dried leaves were dropped on it). The length of the organism from the tip of one leg to the tip of another leg (directly across the body) is about 6-7 centimeters. The organism was moving very slow across the web and seemed lazy. The organism is white. The body of the organism is oval shaped.

description: The insect was observed in an oak woodland on an overcast/rainy day. The insect was found approximately 1-2 meters from the trail, near a large boulder and a very mossy oak tree. There were about 5-7 insects that looked similar to the one observed (the other organisms had the same physiological features but different coloration) in the same 3 foot by 3 foot area. The insect was very active and "jumpy". Its body was about 2- 2.5 inches long. The insect has two large antennae that are approximately the same length of the body. The two back legs of the insect are thicker and longer than the front 4 legs. The back legs have diagonal striations and are thick from the base of the leg (where it attaches to the thorax) to the leg joint. After the joint the legs become very thin. The insect appears to have a foot-like part on the bottom of all its legs (which could possible aid with climbing). On the end of the abdomen, there is a tail-like protrusion that comes to a pointed end. Where this protrusion attaches to the abdomen there are two "points" that stick out. The thorax covers part of the abdomen and resembles a shield. The abdomen is segmented and is the biggest section of the insects body. The insect is light tan/white in color.

description: This buckeye butterfly was found on the trail near 4/5 ant nests. The weather was overcast/rainy (the temperature was about 65 degrees Fahrenheit) and the butterfly was very lazy (which allowed the capture of the butterfly). The outside of the wings were yellow/white/tan and blended in well with the ground. The body and part of the wing nearest the body are very hairy. There appears to be some "dust" on the upper wings of the butterfly. The eyes of the butterfly are brown and have a unique texture. The antennae of the butterfly are thin and white with round black tips. The butterfly is not fully outstretched, but part of the second spot on the lower wing is visible.

description: The purple flower was found along the edge of a vernal pool along a slight incline by an ant nest. There were approximately 30-40 plants in the same area. On our hike back I observed the same flower along the edges of other pools and streams. The flowers had long stalks with flowers that branched off the main stalk about 2/3 of the way off the plant. The flowers themselves are "puffs" that decrease in size towards the top of the plant, creating a cone shape. The plant is approximately 30-45 cm tall and the flowers begin about 15 cm up the plant. The flowers are clustered above the bigger leaves of the plant. There are approximately 2-3 small leaves below the flower "puffs". The plant had a slight mint/herb fragrance. Some of the plants had died, some where in full bloom, and others were budding. Twelve days after making this initial observation, I hiked to another pond, during a particularly hot/sunny day, and observed that many bees were attracted to the flower. When I observed there flowers on July 9th, the weather was overcast/rainy and I did not see any bees or other insects (other than the ants in the ant nest) around the plant.

description: Observed a pond near the edge and concealed in the reeds. The weather was overcast/rainy. It had a green body and brown/olive legs. Approximately 3-5 in the same 2 foot by 2 foot area (many of the other "frogs" I saw were very tiny, so there could have been more than what I observed). It has a white-ish underside. The organism was very active, it continuously crawled around the container. The underside of the legs are yellowish in color. The frog has 4 toes on its front two legs and 3 toes on its back 2 legs. On the green back of the organism there are black spots with black lines on the sides of its backside. It has black stripes which extend from the outer side of the face (at the base of the neck) behind the eyes and towards the center (above the mouth area) of the face, but do not touch in the middle. It has gold colored eyes with black pupils.

description: When I observed this arachnid, it was rainy/overcast and the temperature was around 65 degrees Fahrenheit. The arachnid was found walking over the pond and along the edge of the pond. It has eight hairy legs. The legs of the arachnid appear to have a dark black and light tan stripe pattern (the stripes are very thin). The head of the spider is more elongated than the thorax. The head is a light brown color with white and black designs on top of the brown. The thorax of the arachnid is mainly black with(what looks like) two darker parallel stripes sunning through. It also has two attachments on its head near the mouth. There were 30-40 arachnids (of different/same species) in the same area (5 foot by 5 foot area). It has a large abdomen that is oval/circular shaped. The abdomen is a tan color with white "edges" towards the underside of the arachnid. The arachnid was very active when it was caught.

description: The grasshopper was found within 2 feet of a pond in wet/damp reeds. The grasshopper was approximately 2 cm long. The wings of the organism are slightly longer than the abdomen. From an overhead view, top of the wings change from red to white to tan to black at the base. The outside surface of the wings are yellow/tan and have black spots. It has black eyes that are slightly clouded. The antennae of the grasshopper are not located on the tope of its head, they are located under the eyes of the grasshopper. There is an attachment above each of the eyes of the grasshopper (it resembles an attachments on mandibles that aid in eating). The underside of the thorax/abdomen of the grasshopper is segmented and white/tan in color. The underside of the head and legs of the grasshopper are yellow/tan in color. It has horizontal and thick black stripes on its back legs that stop after the joint. The grasshopper has a black head (top view). The black color continues to the thorax, but turns into a rough hourglass shape and then becomes completely black again.  There were approximately 5-10 other species of grasshoppers in the same area ( 2 foot by 2 foot area).

description: When the grasshopper was observed the weather was very overcast and rainy (the temperature was about 65 degrees Fahrenheit). It was found approximately 4/5 meters from a pond. The grasshopper was caught in the reeds/grass that was flattened and wet. Approximately 10 grasshoppers in the same area. The grasshopper was about 2 cm in length. The antennae were smaller than the 4 front legs. It has 4 attachments on the mandible (that probably aid in eating). The grasshopper has black designs on its back (head, thorax, and abdomen) and on its back legs. The patterns on its back legs are horizontal black stripes. The underside of the organism is tan and segmented. The wings do not run the full length of the body, they start at the back of the head and stop between the first and second legs. I believe there is a forewing that covers the actual wings of the grasshopper. The forewing is black with a small dot. When I observed the grasshopper hoping, it did not utilize its wings and mostly used its back legs to jump. It has burgundy/brown eyes and has hairy legs. It also made a loud "clicking" noise when it jumped. The front four legs were thin and short compared to the thick, bent, and powerful hind legs of the organism (the organism used these legs to hop with).  The markings on the organism are very symmetrical. I believe that this grasshopper is an example of a fifth instar stage and is not an full grown adult migratory grasshopper because the wings of the grasshopper do not run the full length of the body.

description: This praying mantis was found in a grassland area during a very sunny day (the temperature was around 80 degrees Fahrenheit). The color of the mantis was pale yellow/ white, which matched the color of the grass around it. The praying mantis was 12 -14 cm in length. The mantis was very active (it crawled all over my arms, hands, and a net). The head of the mantis was the shape of a triangle with a rounded base.The eyes of the mantis were a slightly darker yellow than the body of the mantis and were located on the sides of the head. The pupils in the eyes of the mantis are very black and very small (about the same size as the tip of a pin). Its antennae are a slightly darker color than its body and are smaller than the second set of legs. The mantis has a distinct black marking on the inside upper part of its front legs that resembles a oval shape. The front legs of the mantis are the most "developed". They have a smaller/thinner upper segment, a thick/elongated middle section of the leg, and a small "foot" than has two "attachments". The middle segment of the mantis leg are serrated on the bottom of the leg. The thorax has a striated texture and is the same color as the entire body of the mantis.

description: The newt was found in a small pool about 5.5 feet in diameter and 1/2 feet deep. The pool was located in an oak forest in a dry creek bed. A small stream (an extremely small stream that was probably only a few centimeters deep), that ran across the trail and downhill towards the pool,  fed the creek. Although there were many leaves, branches, and other debris in the pool, the water was clear. When the bottom of the pool was disturbed, the water became cloudy. There were approximately 5-7 Northern Rough Skin Newts in the pool and possibly 1-2 California newts. The rough skin newt has a dark grey/brown back (that blended in very well with the bottom of the pool) and a bright orange underside. One California Rough Skin Newt was about 4/5 inches in length and another was about 8 inches in length. One newt came up for air during this observation, so the bright orange belly could be easily observed. A wasp nest was also found close by (approximately 3-5 feet downstream). There was about 75-80% canopy cover over the pool.

description: The grasshopper was found in a grassland. When we caught this grasshopper there were approximately 10 -20 more grasshoppers in the same area ( a 2 foot by 2 foot area). This organism was very small, around 1.2 cm in length. When the organism was caught it was bright/sunny and around 80 degrees Fahrenheit. On the hind legs of the organism, there are medium/light green markings on the joint of the legs (where the leg bends). The hindmost legs also have a white stripe running down top of the legs (can be see from an overhead view in the pictures). The organism is white/ light tan on the bottom and a yellow/tan color on the back of the grasshopper. The grasshopper has a distinguishing tan/light brown stripe that starts at its head and runs down the entire length of its body. The large stripe down its body is "framed in" with a line of white. It has 2 attachments on its mandible,  small antennae (smaller than the first two front legs, but bigger than the attachments on the mandible) and large hind legs (bigger than the size of the front 4 legs). I believe this organism is a grasshopper because its antennae are short.

description: This grasshopper is about 2.5 cm long with antennae of approximately the same length. It appears to have 2 long and thin wing-like things that stretch almost the length of its body. It is tan with alternating darker markings, ranging from dark brown to black. It has 6 legs but its back legs have symmetrical black marks that go in a vertical direction while its back has symmetrical diagonal markings. Its underside is segmented and lighter in color, more of a light beige. It has a black curved tail-like thing. It has two big yellow eyes and 4 mouth feelers. It was found in grassland that was about 2 feet high but had been recently inhabited by cows so much of the grass was stomped down and eaten at the top. The grasshopper was jumping around when captured and kept moving around and appeared anxious when it was captured while taking pictures. When released it quickly hopped away.

description: I am not sure if this is a grasshopper or what species of grasshopper it is. Found in grassland. When the organism was captured it was very active and jumpy. It also made a loud "clicking" noise when it jumped. It was tannish with black markings along its back and hind legs. On its hind legs, the black markings were horizontal stripes that ran down the length of the leg. The organism was about 2 cm long. It has six legs, two antennae, and 4 attachments on the mandible (possibly to aid with eating). The front four legs were thin and short compared to the thick, bent, and powerful hind legs of the organism (the organism used these legs to hop with). The antennae are shorter than the four front legs. The markings on the organism are very symmetrical and the body is segmented. I believe that this grasshopper is an example of a fifth instar stage and is not an full grown adult migratory grasshopper because the wings of the grasshopper do not run the full length of the body.

description: Found between the edge of an oak forest and a Chaparral. When the species was observed it was sunny (approximately 80 degrees Fahrenheit). When I touched the leaves of the plant, a non-sticky "sap" gave my fingers a citrus/ herb scent (the scent smelled like the taste of the new green tips of a Douglass fir). The flower grew in rocky/ arid soil on the edge of the trail and there was no shade or tree cover over the plant. There were approximately 20 -30 plants within an 5 foot by 5 foot area. As we continued our hike, I spotted more of the plant clustered together on the sides of the trail, on rocky hillsides, and in a grassland area. The flowers themselves are white in color. This flower has 3 petals on either side with spaces in between the petals, but when I observed other flowers they had petals all the way around the middle of the flower (with no spaces in between). The flower also has very small flowers (3 in the picture) located in the middle of the big flower. The stems of the flowers are red/brown in color and the leaves of the plant are light/medium green. The diameter of the flower was approximately 2 cm. On some of the flowers it looked like part of the flower had not bloomed yet (it was still budding) or had fallen off by though an indeterminate cause. The size, amount of budding, and amount of petals/small flowers varied with all the flowers on each individual plant. The height of each plant was approximately 1/2 -1 1/2 feet tall.

The entire body of the beetle is approximately 2 cm long and 1 1/2 cm wide. The feet of the beetle were red in color. description: When I observed this butterfly, it was foggy/ overcast (the temperature was not over 75 degrees Fahrenheit). It was found in a grassland clearing on the edge of a Douglass fir forest. The butterfly landed on a stalk near the base of a grass stem (not sure what species of grass). The wingspan of the butterfly (horizontally from right tip to left tip) was approximately 5 inches. The body of the butterfly was thin, furry/hairy, and about 1- 1 1/2 inches in length. The butterfly was "lazy" and did not flutter away when the camera was placed very close (the camera was approximately an inch away from the organism) which may be due to the lack of sun during this observation. I believe this is a buckeye butterfly, but I am not sure if the buckeye is a common buckeye butterfly or a subspecies (Junonia coenia coenia). I also saw 1-2 other buckeye butterflies in the same area. The buckeye did not fully spread its wings, so the spots/ "eyes" on the top of the second wing were not entirely visible. The body of the butterfly is a medium/dark grey/brown. This coloring of the body continues onto the wings, but in a lighter hue. There are two orange stripes on the top of the top wing.

description: I used a wildflower field guide to identify this chicory flower. I believe it is Cichorium intybus, but the stamens of the flower are curled instead of straight (as seen in the field guide pictures). I am not sure if the plant I found is a separate species of flower or if it is a subspecies of Cichorium intybus. I found the flower in a grassland that was on the edge of a forest. There was only one plant within the small area. The plant had approximately 6-8 flowers and had many stems that branched off from the base of the plant. The leaves of the plant were only found at the base of the plant and towards the bottom of the stems (in other words the leaves were not found near the flowers, which were located at the top of the plant). There were grasses (not sure what species) and yellow flowers (not sure what species) around the Cichorium intybus plant. The plant was approximately 2 feet tall from the base of the plant (where the plant met the ground) to the flowers at the top of the plant. The flowers were a periwinkle blue in color, about 18- 27 inches in circumference and about 6-9 inches in diameter. Inside some of the flowers, at the base of the filaments, there were black ants (not sure what species) and a buckeye butterfly was found in the same area (less than a foot away from the plant).  On the day I took this observation, it was foggy/overcast and the temperature was not more than 75 degrees Fahrenheit.

His pedipalps  were very large for his small body and he looked like he was cleaning his leg I tarsus with his pedipalps before and after entering the female's web. The male stayed in a corner of the web the entire time I observed the pair. There were no other sightings of other male orb weavers. Male had pale carapace and darker abdomen with markings like that of the banded garden spider male.

The spider was large, with 1.5 centimeter long abdomen, .7 centimeter long carapace and 2 centimeter long legs. There were tons of baby frogs jumping around the pong and two were stuck in the spider's web. The frogs were only about 3 centimeters long and the spider was eating one with another secured to the side of the web. The spider's web was an orb web and had a layer of tangle web in front and behind the orb web. There was one other orb weaver slightly larger than this one on the other side of the pond. This orb weaver had the same style of web.

description: This insect is believe to be a true bug, but some speculation shows that it could be a beetle. Through some rough research, this insect is type of stink bug nymph--possibly the Harlequin Cabbage Bug Nymph. The insect was about 4 mm long. It was found at around 11:50 am during a sunny and hot day where the temperature was about 80 degrees Fahrenheit. When I took these pictures, the insect was running along the branch. This insect was found on a Ceanothus Branch which was along the Leopard Lilly Trail on the preserve
